 {"id": "franken_networkx-wicalgerr", "title": "REVIEW: [LOW] within_inter_cluster raised NetworkXError; nx raises NetworkXAlgorithmError", "description": "nx.within_inter_cluster raises NetworkXAlgorithmError('No community information available for Node X') when a node lacks the community attribute. fnx previously raised NetworkXError with a different message ('Set node attribute community first'). Callers catching the algorithm-error base class diverged. Fixed to raise the exact nx exception type + message.", "status": "closed", "priority": 4, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Use NetworkXAlgorithmError + nx message", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-chaindec", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] chain_decomposition was a no-op on any cyclic graph", "description": "fnx.chain_decomposition delegated to a Rust binding that returned an empty iterator for every graph with cycles (triangle, K4-minus-edge, two-triangles, K4). Only trees produced correct (empty) output. Since chain_decomposition is a primitive for cycle-basis / 2-edge-connectivity work, any caller relying on it silently got wrong behavior. Fix: route through _call_networkx_for_parity so nx's reference DFS-based decomposition drives the output; all probed graphs now return non-empty chain lists that span the correct edge set.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to nx reference impl", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-smallrng", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] sigma/omega diverged from nx for same (G, seed, nrand)", "description": "nx.sigma and nx.omega use @py_random_state to obtain a stateful RNG that is threaded through all inner random_reference/lattice_reference calls, so each of the nrand iterations advances the RNG and consumes different reference graphs. fnx had its own local loop using Python stdlib Random and per-iteration seed derivation via rng.randint(0, 2**31), producing different numeric results for the same (G, seed, nrand) inputs. Delegated to nx via _call_networkx_for_parity; fnx still keeps the early type/size error-path checks (NetworkXNotImplemented on multigraph/directed, NetworkXError on <4 nodes) so the fast-fail behavior is unchanged.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate scalar computation to nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-trophdir", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] trophic_levels/differences/incoherence accepted undirected input silently", "description": "nx.trophic_levels, nx.trophic_differences, and nx.trophic_incoherence_parameter are @not_implemented_for('undirected') and raise NetworkXNotImplemented. fnx's local implementations ran the numpy linalg.solve on the undirected adjacency anyway, producing meaningless results (e.g. all-nodes-at-4.8e16). Users calling these on an undirected graph by mistake got silent garbage with no error signal. Gate each wrapper on G.is_directed() and delegate directed cases to nx for exact parity (including the int-vs-float type for the first node, which fnx's numpy path was widening to float).", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Directed-only gate + delegate to nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-daglongundir", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] dag_longest_path_length raised NetworkXError on undirected; nx raises NetworkXNotImplemented", "description": "The Rust binding translated 'undirected' rejection as NetworkXError; nx uses @not_implemented_for('undirected') which raises NetworkXNotImplemented. Callers catching the capability-signal exception class (NetworkXNotImplemented base) would miss the signal. Added an is_directed() gate that raises NetworkXNotImplemented('not implemented for undirected type') with the exact nx wording.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python-side class-correct gate", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-domtype", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] dominating_set returned list; nx (and fnx's own docstring) says set", "description": "nx.dominating_set returns a Python set. The Rust binding returned a list. The docstring already claimed set, so users doing set ops (issubset, intersection, union) on the result silently broke. Coerce the Rust return to set when the native path is used; the nx-parity delegation branch already returns a set.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Coerce to set on native path", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-wlhash", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] weisfeiler_lehman_graph_hash produced different hashes than nx for the same graph", "description": "fnx's local WL implementation seeded initial labels with str(degree) and hashed with blake2b, while nx's scheme seeds empty (or node_attr) with a different multiset hashing strategy that changed in nx v3.5. Hashes diverged for the same graph+args, so fnx and nx cannot be used interchangeably as graph fingerprinters. Delegate to nx for exact parity.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-wlsubhash", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] weisfeiler_lehman_subgraph_hashes missing include_initial_labels kwarg + wrong output", "description": "nx.weisfeiler_lehman_subgraph_hashes has a ``include_initial_labels=False`` kwarg (default False). fnx's signature was missing that kwarg entirely AND the implementation unconditionally prepended the initial-label hash to each node's list, yielding iterations+1 hashes per node vs nx's iterations. Also used a different internal hashing scheme so even the hash strings differed. Delegate to nx so signature, length, and hash values all match.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Add kwarg + delegate to nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
